commit_message:
Allow describe_instances to use tags for searches

In the EC2 API, the DescribeInstances API call allows for a 'filter'
argument to be passed, consisting of key/value filter pairs.  If the
filter contains tag:<something> or tag-<something>, the search is done
on resource tags.

See
http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/APIReference/ApiReference-query-DescribeInstances.html
for details of the API and

http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/Using_Tags.html for
usage.

Change-Id: If2622c4dacbdd3a53fd6d49242225692da8b741a
Signed-off-by: Stephen Gran <stephen.gran@guardian.co.uk>

[{'created': '2013-04-04 23:08:09.000000000', 'message': "Implements self-hosting capabilities for Marconi debugging and development.

bin/marconi-self-host launches the platform and serves up http on the
host IP and port of your choosing.  Reasonable defaults are provided
for the IP, port, and configuration file.

Self-hosting allows you to run the entire application entirely within the
confines of Python -- avoiding uwsgi altogehter and simplifying the setting
of break points and debugging.

Also changed was the sample marconi configuration file, allowing it to
be used essentially out of the box with these self-hosting capabilities.

Note that the port designation was deleted for the WSGI transport. This
isn't really being used, and was being confused with the http port one
specifies in the uwsgi configuration.

commit_message:
Implements self-hosting capabilities for Marconi debugging

bin/marconi-self-host launches the platform and serves up
http on the host IP and port of your choosing.  Reasonable
defaults are provided for the IP, port, and configuration file.

Self-hosting allows you to run the entire application entirely
within the confines of Python -- avoiding uwsgi altogehter and
simplifying the setting of break points and debugging.

Also changed was the sample marconi configuration file, allowing
it to be used essentially out of the box with these self-hosting
capabilities.

Note that the port designation was deleted for the WSGI transport.
This isn't really being used, and was being confused with the http
port one specifies in the uwsgi configuration.

Change-Id: I30b161591fc26d4db70d37ec0a6a492f8b7958e6

commit_message:
Handle maxclonepervolume/node limits in SF driver.

The SolidFire cluster has a max simultaneous clones per volume and node
limt that we weren't accounting for.  Add some logic to detect this situation
and loop until enough simultaneous clones are completed to allow processing
of the next one in line.

Fixes bug: 1129810

Cherry picked from Grizzly sumbit: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/22395

Change-Id: I5d4920001be2757463c03ada3274107e32d7cdee

commit_message:
Add volume_type checking to SolidFire driver.

This change simply adds the expected volume_type check
to the create volume method.  This specifically checks
for QoS settings based on Volume_Type extra-specs which is
the standard method of driver specific settings in Folsom.

This is a selective import of the changes in Grizzly
  I4b39b301b9a1f9b859a694decfee48c74d22a74a

Change-Id: I01ea0389090c0294df5f75a4d7ab31c5c37f7a29

commit_message:
Fix Network object encoding issue when using qpid

When creating network via REST API will throw the exception
"CodecException: no encoding for
<nova.db.sqlalchemy.models.Network object at 0x4a8ea10>".
It only occurs when using qpid.
Fix this issue through using jsonutils.to_primitive method.

Fix bug 1143584.

Change-Id: I833aef451f8e3d5eaa246c19d67b2474a9d36910
(cherry picked from commit b4d43b0d0c890ccb940862719c6b88a24029d44a)

[{'created': '2013-04-05 12:50:39.000000000', 'message': "Refactoring for swift systemd on Fedora 17/18.

Updates the Swift storage modules so that they support
systemd on Fedora and using init scripts on RHEL. In order to start
services on Fedora we'll want to have access to the port when we
start the systemd services.

Changes include:

1) Add a new bind_port option to generic.pp. This is now passed in from
storage/server.pp so that each service knows its port.

2) Update generic so that it supports configuring
account/container/object services. This DRY's things up and solves the
issue of having to propigate bind_port all over the place.

3) Remove the (private) storage modules for account/container/object.
See #2 above for why these are no longer needed.

4) Recent RHEL and Fedora openstack packages include init scripts to
 startup replicator services so we can remove the custom replicator
startup provider.

This change keeps some custom Ubuntu logic that works around some
packaging issues on that platform.

Change-Id: Ib0ed7c600e7d0cb374437eb4e7b2c1f5e99e795f
"}]
commit_message:
Refactoring for swift systemd on Fedora 17/18.

Updates the Swift storage modules so that they support
systemd on Fedora and using init scripts on RHEL. In order to start
services on Fedora we'll want to have access to the port when we
start the systemd services.

Changes include:

1) Add a new bind_port option to generic.pp. This is now passed in from
storage/server.pp so that each service knows its port.

2) Update generic so that it supports configuring
account/container/object services. This DRY's things up and solves the
issue of having to propigate bind_port all over the place.

3) Remove the (private) storage modules for account/container/object.
See #2 above for why these are no longer needed.

4) Recent RHEL and Fedora openstack packages include init scripts to
 startup replicator services so we can remove the custom replicator
startup provider.

This change keeps some custom Ubuntu logic that works around some
packaging issues on that platform.

Change-Id: Ib0ed7c600e7d0cb374437eb4e7b2c1f5e99e795f

commit_message:
Only call getLogger after configuring logging.

Logging needs to be setup properly before we try to log
something. Fix a test case that loads the code but does
not execute the code that results in the LOG being setup
properly.

Fixes LP# 1161031

Change-Id: I9d5bc6b87cfb25243f00e17b532d4485dc4454e4

commit_message:
Make "multi_host" True when it is set to 'T' in network_create.

Fixes bug 1161297
Even if creating a network with the "--multi_host=T", the "multi_host"
property of the new network is still "False".
This is because nova server interprets 'T' to "False".
This patch fixes the problem.

commit_message:
Added gunicorn as server application manager

This patch adds gunicorn as dependency for starting and managing server
workers. Gunicorn allow users to chose whether to use workers based on a
sync process, eventlet or gevent. It also manages multiple workers, ssl,
process uid, process gid.

Implements blueprint transport-base

Change-Id: Ic328dbb937f8df69691911c6e6ff6b318bb1db34

commit_message:
Combine localrc files

Use the Grenade devstack.localrc.* files as the 'default' for DevStack
by pre-pending them to the devstack-vm-gate.sh generated localrc.

devstack.localrc is now appended to the combined DevStack localrc
to still allow it to be the final config.  Normally this will be empty.

Change-Id: I18cb963c4baeeeb447bcb1436521100f1372882a

commit_message:
Move Dom0 modifications to the install manual

This change moves the configure for migrations/resize instructions to
the install section, as it is a Dom0 modification, so it fits better to
the post-installation notes for XenServer.

Patchset just does minor grammar fix (a/an, mount point two words)

Change-Id: Ia719b9876b090f99f56b193602f8f65d1c887bd3

commit_message:
remove database-initialization from openstack-db:

Database initialization is different for bootstrap node,
vs. first baremetal database node, so database init,
should happen outside the openstack-db element.

Change-Id: I25dcd2e8e5ffa1a11128785a73f6a29c49e6f174

commit_message:
NetApp[backport]: Fix for snapshot not deleted in error state.

This fix enables cleaning of volumes/snapshots
in error state by allowing them to delete.
It will allow the delete call to be
successful if snapshot/volume are in
error state. This also fixes the bug
raised recently with  number 1145409 which seems
to be duplicate of 1143661.

bug 1143661
bug 1145409

Change-Id: I38bc13e676404f96db54b12edfa56680489e893e

commit_message:
Sync rpc changes from oslo stable/folsom

Contains code from the following oslo commits:

9f938720 Update common code to support pep 1.3.
7e36792c kombu's fanout_cast_to_server was calling wrong method
 - Fixes bug 1074113
c3ec615c LOG.exception() should only be used in exception handler
17c5188c Use pep8 v1.3.3
d147d9f2 Fix QPID reconnect issues
 - Fixes bug 1073999

Change-Id: Ia4504cb4d8f2108b743efc4639450254d6e3fb8e

commit_message:
Implemented marconi-server entry point

This patch adds the first console_script for marconi server.

In order to use it it's enough to run setup.py either using develop or
install.

Side changes:
    The config now uses sys.argv[1:] if no custom cli args have been
    set.

Implements blueprint transport-base

Change-Id: I15732129d66b32fca2b818e9105b17f541094983

commit_message:
Queue stats in MongoDB.

The patch implements stats methods for mongodb's queue controller and
uses the `MessageController.active` method to get valid messages present
in the queue.

Implements: blueprint storage-mongodb

Change-Id: I8a2d32ebeef9a8dd4b2131b522f026d9c5d0cd6e

commit_message:
If a stack create fails, ensure the stack is deleteable

The resource delete operation attempts to delete CREATE_FAILED
resources.  Further it attempts to delete resources that were
not created during a creation operation because further processing
of the template does not take place.

This patch special cases these two conditions in the delete operation.

Change-Id: I1c83ba68754f38a0f7e91e77fcf02177c457504e
Fixes: Bug #1155824

commit_message:
don't regenerate keys for keystone

keystone doesn't need keys regenerated after it's upgraded, so

commit_message:
Check for malformed JSON when creating a queue.

Meanwhile,
    1. Dumps UTF-8 JSON in response;
    2. Set Content-Location for GET.

Implements: blueprint transport-wsgi

Change-Id: I04c988168366f60cf88a0693bab50ded5b855117

commit_message:
Enable direct testing with nosetests

This is the minimal backport of
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/21685/
which makes it possible to run the functional
tests without also invoking run_tests.sh. The
extra call to monkey_patch is not causing any
harm when used via run_tests.sh

Change-Id: If0d2cb94f956380a2c35414b6e8df6db76a669c6

[{'created': '2013-04-03 07:50:45.000000000', 'message': 'Remove gettext.install from ceilometer/__init__.py

The gettext.install() installs a builtin _() function for translation
purpose. If it is called multiple times, the last call will win and the
translation domain set by the last call will be used.

When the ceilometer.compute.nova_notifier driver used within nova, the
gettext.install() call in ceilometer/__init__.py would change the
previous translation domain set by nova. This is not what we want.

We have to remove this shortcut, and put the gettext.install() call
early on in a top level script.

Instead of directly calling gettext.install(), we leverage the
gettextutils.install() in openstack.common, so we can specifiy the
localedir for ceilometer through the environment variable
CEILOMETER_LOCALEDIR.

This is part of the blueprint gettext-i18n-issue.

commit_message:
Remove gettext.install from ceilometer/__init__.py

The gettext.install() installs a builtin _() function for translation
purpose. If it is called multiple times, the last call will win and the
translation domain set by the last call will be used.

When the ceilometer.compute.nova_notifier driver used within nova, the
gettext.install() call in ceilometer/__init__.py would change the
previous translation domain set by nova. This is not what we want.

We have to remove this shortcut, and put the gettext.install() call
early on in a top level script.

Instead of directly calling gettext.install(), we leverage the
gettextutils.install() in openstack.common, so we can specifiy the
localedir for ceilometer through the environment variable
CEILOMETER_LOCALEDIR.

This is part of the blueprint gettext-i18n-issue.

Change-Id: Icb2dcfb319778042cf569dcb607f579d1e0fda3a

commit_message:
Update part of openstack.common.

Updated the gettextutils and log module in openstack.common.

Not update the openstack.common for the followings. We might need to
update those after we offically release grizzly.
- notifier: removed deprecated grizzly features.
- rpc: enable message envelop.

This is part of the blueprint gettext-i18n-issue.

Change-Id: Iac01c5d66f58518341d84da7948356fc4487d171

[{'created': '2013-04-05 10:01:25.000000000', 'message': 'Add expected IDs to router.interface.* notifications

Fixes bug 1160431

The router.interface.{create|delete} notifications are intended to be
consumed by ceilometer, but did not include the router or tenant IDs
in the RPC message payload. Ceilometer requires both these data for
metering purposes.

The missing UUIDs are now provided in the notifications.

Change-Id: I1ca6e1d5377100a0549293e0bdff0182711c750f
'}]
commit_message:
Add expected IDs to router.interface.* notifications

Fixes bug 1160431

The router.interface.{create|delete} notifications are intended to be
consumed by ceilometer, but did not include the router or tenant IDs
in the RPC message payload. Ceilometer requires both these data for
metering purposes.

The missing UUIDs are now provided in the notifications.

Change-Id: I1ca6e1d5377100a0549293e0bdff0182711c750f

commit_message:
Return an empty string rather than None when calling repr()

Repr() should return "a string containing a printable representation of
an object," which is a convention Sphinx 1.2 relies on when building
the docs.

Fixes bug 1163369

Change-Id: Ieefd69c5b4b521500679df7745f60cb3a4d2f77c
(cherry picked from commit 29cb3251afd65fdd0a98b76d58f05458aaab3b47)

commit_message:
Prevents a portinfo deletion in vm migration with NEC plugin.

Fixes: Bug 1160193

This patch prevents a portinfo deletion at the end of the migration sequence
by ignoring port_removed message from the source host.

commit_message:
Adds support for the DHCP DNS domain search option (RFC 3397) per subnet

Added dns_searchdomains to Subnet
If dns_searchdomain is specified, then write dhcp option in dnsmasq conf
Modified api to allow dns_searchdomains to be set
Updated linux_dhcp test cases to include the domain search option

Change-Id: I57d45d1664a18d89fbb46bcc74c2a09f8b786e0b
Fixes: bug #1108644

commit_message:
quantum/agent/firewall.py: __metaclass__ is not set while @abstractmethod

While FirewallDriver uses abstracetmethod, __metaclass__ is not set
to ABCMeta.
So set its metaclass to ABCMeta and fixes the issue.

Fixes: bug #1119119
Signed-off-by: Isaku Yamahata <yamahata@valinux.co.jp>
Change-Id: Idcde3ca2e55d1f95fa4d23db2a6a1366d68b0c83

the same host. A new configuration variable has been added to
ensure backward compatibility.

is running.

At the moment I always receive the full exception in the
logs when the consoleauth service is not available after
deleting an instance. I think an ERROR message in the logs
is sufficient.

'}]
commit_message:
handle timouts of requests send to consoleauth

At the moment I always receive the full exception in the
logs when the consoleauth service is not available after
deleting an instance. I think an ERROR message in the logs
is sufficient.

Change-Id: If68862d97d51d00fc8d2385bcbd3c89a7ccc93dd

 * flake8 supports more checks than pep8 (e.g. detection of
   unused imports and variables), and has an extension mechanism.
   A plugin to support automatic HACKING validation is planned.

commit_message:
Switch to flake8 from pep8.

 * flake8 supports more checks than pep8 (e.g. detection of
   unused imports and variables), and has an extension mechanism.
   A plugin to support automatic HACKING validation is planned.
 * See: http://flake8.readthedocs.org/

Change-Id: I8c9314c606802109a4d01908dbc74ecb792ad0ac

[{'created': '2013-04-04 22:42:05.000000000', 'message': 'Pass correct options to glance client in examples.

The current python-glanceclient has changed --disk_format to
--disk-format and --container_format to --container-format; also the
--file option must be immediately followed by the name of the file.

commit_message:
Pass correct options to glance client in examples.

The current python-glanceclient has changed --disk_format to
--disk-format and --container_format to --container-format; also the
--file option must be immediately followed by the name of the file.

Change-Id: I26228c10c9280dbb1574c4f59f0330623ef3ce81

commit_message:
CharFields replaced by IntegerFields in LBaaS forms.

The following fields were changed:
* Vip / protocol port
* Vip / connection limit
* Member / protocol port
* Member / weight
* Monitor / delay
* Monitor / timeout
* Monitor / max_retries

Added range validations:
* Vip / protocol port -- in range [1..65535]
* Vip / connection limit -- more or equal that 0 or -1 if the limit is not set
* Member / protocol port -- in range [1..65535]
* Member / weight -- in range [0..256]
* Monitor / delay -- more or equal that 1
* Monitor / timeout -- more or equal that 1
* Monitor / max_retries -- in range [1..10]

Fixes bug 1153525

Change-Id: I7bf9fe24060dc85076d9be2e6592a51a33fefeae

Since when does a HEAD against a segmented object return content-length 0?

curl -i -H 'X-Auth-Token: AUTH_tk9c7e98287cb840ca9ce56c1c492a1db5' http://127.0.0.1:8080/v1/AUTH_dfg/hat/setup.py -XHEAD

Date: Tue, 02 Apr 2013 17:21:02 GMT'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2013-04-02 18:21:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

This didn't work for me when I functionally tested it by lowering my container_listing_limit in swift.conf[swift-constraints].  I still got back "Content-Length: 0"

I did notice that the proxy will accurately build the content-length on HEAD requests to a multipart-manifest object if the segments fit in the first page of the listing (there's an second listing request there too, maybe unwanted? http://paste.openstack.org/show/35144/).  But, so this change really only effects large objects with more than 10K segments.

But if really want consistency shouldn't HEAD's set the transfer-encoding and omit the content-length header?  http://paste.openstack.org/show/35142/'}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2013-04-02 18:30:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

David, functional test won't do it since functional test does
not actually query the database. That is why it still shows 0."}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2013-04-02 18:37:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The previous message should be for Clay. 
For David comment, as indicated in the patch comment, this
patch only affects segmented object which has more segments
than the container_listing_limits allows. To test this behavior, you can use swift client to upload an object and
split into small segments, say 1000 bytes, then set your
container_listing_limits to be like 10. So you have more
segments for that object than 10, now if you do HEAD request,
the content length will be 0. However, if you do GET, the
content length will be correct. This is bad because HEAD and
GET requests should return exactly same headers. Also for
very large objects, you as a client do not want to start
download before you know how big it is. HEAD request can
accomplish this. This patch also makes the swift really
compliant with the rfc 2616 specification.'}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2013-04-02 18:41:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Clay said that "But if really want consistency shouldn't HEAD's set the transfer-encoding and omit the content-length header? http://paste.openstack.org/show/35142/"

Not really, this is for the HEAD request against a segmented
object. not for GET. HEAD response does not have a body, thus
it does not make any sense to have the transfer-encoding.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-04-02 18:55:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

You know, I think Clay has a good point (transfer-encoding notwithstanding). If a GET response doesn't have a Content-Length header in it, then the HEAD response shouldn't either.

Also, it's a whole lot simpler to code up and doesn't require any extra work in the container server."}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2013-04-02 21:32:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-04-02 21:33:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Doesn't seem to work

New patchset patch-id matches previous patchset, but whitespace content has changed.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-04-03 05:26:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

- http://logs.openstack.org/25914/3/check/gate-tempest-devstack-vm-postgres-full/11122 : SUCCESS
'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-04-03 18:29:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Do not merge

As far as standards-compliance goes, RFC 2616 section 9.4 says "The HEAD method is identical to GET except that the server MUST NOT return a message-body in the response. The metainformation contained in the HTTP headers in response to a HEAD request SHOULD be identical to the information sent in response to a GET request."

Given a large object manifest /a/c/manifest with >= 10K segments, the response to "GET /v1/a/c/manifest" does not include a Content-Length header.

Therefore, the response to "HEAD /v1/a/c/manifest" should not include a Content-Length header.

I don't want to see Swift doing a bunch of work to calculate a value for a header that shouldn't even be there.'}, {'account_id': 995, 'date': '2013-04-03 18:52:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I agree with Sam.  After the discussion yesterday the one feature that seemed to be needed was that a client could see the size of a >10,000 segment object. This can be accomplished (as clay suggested) by using the Manifest header returned from the HEAD and querying the segment container itself. That doesn't seem like an overly complicated client solution (esp. for such an edge case) and saves swift from some having some server side problems."}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2013-04-03 19:45:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

David, not true. If you do a get against the segment container itself, it will respond with the segment lists which
limits to the container_listing_limit and the content length
actually is the the length of the response, not the object
size.'}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2013-04-03 19:48:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Sam, how do you know the size a large object? The answer is
you can not. That is what this patch is trying to fix. what
david suggested won't work because he mixed the actual
response body length of querying a container with the
actual object size."}, {'account_id': 995, 'date': '2013-04-03 19:59:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

You could either:

Set it up as 1 container per segmented object, the recommended solution, and HEAD the segment container

or

Query the container specified in the manifest with a prefix and, just like the swiftclient already does for example, requery the container with an end marker until you receive no results from the GET. That way you'd be able to get a complete listing and sum the results."}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2013-04-03 21:07:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

David, are you talking about looking for header 
X-Container-Bytes-Used not the actual content-length header
right?'}, {'account_id': 995, 'date': '2013-04-03 21:28:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

yes. for first option, look at X-Container-Bytes-Used on the container headers and for the second option sum up all the "bytes" returned from the listing'}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2013-04-04 23:39:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Abandoned'}]

[{'created': '2013-04-02 15:35:21.000000000', 'message': 'Swift HEAD request against a segmented object will return content length of zero.

This behavior is not consistent with the GET request. According to rfc 2616,
the headers of the HEAD request and GET request against same object should
be exactly the same.

This patch fixes that problem by query container db and aggregate the size of
each segments. This patch only generate one extra request between proxy server
and container server for segmented object which has more segments than container_
listing_limits allowed. If an object is not a segmented object or its number of
segments is smaller than container_listing_limits, then this code is not executed.

Fixes: bug #1161891

a patch which contains a query into container object table will return the correct content length.

Change-Id: Ic3d6c33a4a323ec1ec4d129084f2c7677dc45953
'}, {'created': '2013-04-02 21:32:54.000000000', 'message': 'Swift HEAD request against a segmented object will return content length of zero.

This behavior is not consistent with the GET request. According to rfc 2616,
the headers of the HEAD request and GET request against same object should
be exactly the same.

This patch fixes that problem by query container db and aggregate the size of
each segments. This patch only generate one extra request between proxy server
and container server for segmented object which has more segments than container_
listing_limits allowed. Further more, this patch is under conrol of the new swift
configuration parameter SUPPORT_LARGE_OBJ_CONTENT_LENGTH_QUERY. If that parameter
is absent or set to False, then the query to the db will not be executed and the
content length for segmented object will be still zero which is how Swift behaves
currently.

Fixes: bug #1161891
Change-Id: Ic3d6c33a4a323ec1ec4d129084f2c7677dc45953
'}, {'created': '2013-04-03 04:45:20.000000000', 'message': 'Swift HEAD request against a segmented object will return content length of zero.

be exactly the same.

This patch fixes that problem by query container db and aggregate the size of
each segments. This patch only generate one extra request between proxy server
and container server for segmented object which has more segments than container_
listing_limits allowed. Further more, this patch is under conrol of the new swift
configuration parameter SUPPORT_LARGE_OBJ_CONTENT_LENGTH_QUERY. If that parameter
is absent or set to False, then the query to the db will not be executed and the
content length for segmented object will be still zero which is how Swift behaves
currently.

Fixes: bug #1161891

commit_message:
Swift HEAD request against a segmented object will return content length of zero.

This behavior is not consistent with the GET request. According to rfc 2616,
the headers of the HEAD request and GET request against same object should
be exactly the same.

This patch fixes that problem by query container db and aggregate the size of
each segments. This patch only generate one extra request between proxy server
and container server for segmented object which has more segments than container_
listing_limits allowed. Further more, this patch is under conrol of the new swift
configuration parameter SUPPORT_LARGE_OBJ_CONTENT_LENGTH_QUERY. If that parameter
is absent or set to False, then the query to the db will not be executed and the
content length for segmented object will be still zero which is how Swift behaves
currently.

Fixes: bug #1161891
Change-Id: Ic3d6c33a4a323ec1ec4d129084f2c7677dc45953

I can reproduce bug 1100771 consistently in my development environment.
Increasing the socket timeout in the SeleniumTestCase class fixes
the timeout issue for me.

This uncovers another issue that causes an "Address already in use
error". This happens because the order of tear down is wrong - we
need to quit() the driver before continuing with tear down rather
than after.

Fixes bug 1100771.

Change-Id: I95fbea05c3fc2516ce4e736eea9b0823bb5bbf79
'}]
commit_message:
Increase socket timeout for selenium tests

I can reproduce bug 1100771 consistently in my development environment.
Increasing the socket timeout in the SeleniumTestCase class fixes
the timeout issue for me.

This uncovers another issue that causes an "Address already in use
error". This happens because the order of tear down is wrong - we
need to quit() the driver before continuing with tear down rather
than after.

Fixes bug 1100771.

Change-Id: I95fbea05c3fc2516ce4e736eea9b0823bb5bbf79

Change-Id: Ibdb48f8a72077b045eeedddfae4c0a1f56098d7a
"}]
commit_message:
Allow a configurable set of TempURL methods

Folks have actually been asking for this. I think they're sending a
DELETE TempURL to someone way ahead of time and the someone issues it
when they're ready. Honestly, I'm not entirely sure of the use case,
but having the set of methods configurable wouldn't hurt.

Change-Id: Ibdb48f8a72077b045eeedddfae4c0a1f56098d7a

This is wrong: /srv/node must be owned by root. In fact, device directories must be owned by root too. Otherwise, if swift-drive-audit unmounts a device, a/c/o servers will write into the node's root filesystem (race is unavoidable despite some convoluted code that tries to avoid it).

So if you really want, add chown root.root /srv/node.

Also, do not add -R to chown. You just created those directories one line up, they are empty!"}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2013-03-22 15:26:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

directory where the disk will be mounted owned by swift user/group, otherwise, it can not create stuff. In the case

stuff will be created at the mounting point.'}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2013-03-25 15:30:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2013-03-25 15:31:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
directory /var/cache/swift /srv/node should be created.

For multiple node swift cluster setup, these directories should be
created in the setup steps. Otherwise, when start up storage servers
there will be errors. The error messages won't tell if it is because
of missing the directory.

Change-Id: I67d74abb7743b76739b5e747d6dcbd3214b00774
Fixes: bug #1158519

commit_message:
ClaimMessage implementation for mongodb

This is a first proposal os ClaimMessage support for the mongodb
storage. Please read comments in the code for a more detailed
explanation of this implementation.

Some issues and race conditions might be found and this implementation
tries to cover them in the best way.

More detailed review is required in the claim creation method

Implements blueprint storage-mongodb

Change-Id: I532fdad895a18dc4961a86adbe7086e9eaa231f9

commit_message:
Resolve conflicting mac address in resize

This patch fixes bug 1161226 and mac address conflicts when migrating or
resizing an instance using the PowerVM driver. This will ensure that if
a migration or resize is taking place on the same host, a temporary mac
address will be assigned to the original LPAR so there is no conflict on
the VIOS when a second LPAR is started with the same address.

Change-Id: I59db484defb789f3a7c0eddbd5ef9e92efc22419

commit_message:
Modify _verify_response to validate response codes.

The method will now take a response code as an additional
parameter and will validate it against the actual one.
Fixes bug 1156684

Change-Id: Idba3f54ed50b359d9230707fb45e7c5ea68e6b7d

I've been thinking about this and I'm not sure this is the right approach (I know I may be in the minority in these opinions, but here they are FWIW):

- cloud-init already depends on boto, so it will need to be in the image regardless of removing the cfntools dependency on it

- This just papers over the real problem, which is (was, I've fixed it, ref keystoneclient patch I posted yesterday) that we don't support AWS v4 signatures (which is why we break with latest boto)

- Our only real dependency (other than the v4 signing, which is a heat/keystone not boto problem) is boto>=2.4.0 (to get the configurable endpoints), this is coming into many (most?) distros now

- It duplicates really quite a lot of code from the heat (and keystoneclient) codebase, this seems like pointless maintenance overhead to me.

- It pins us to an obsolete AWS signature version - I'm assuming they moved to v4 signatures for a reason, very likely v2 has known security vulnerabilities, another huge Ec2Signer cut/paste from keystoneclient will be required to fix this (along with more request formatting logic to support the new format)

- We've talked about moving to a forked aws cfnbootstrap - IMO putting all this effort into our cfntools isn't justified if that is still the plan since we'll end up discarding them?

- IMO our in-instance tools should really talk to the ReST API, then we can just depend on heatclient, I guess these tools would be called something different to avoid conficting names, but provide similar/same functionality.  The aim would be to allow access to all our functionality without requiring the CFN API at all (making it optional like the nova ec2 API).

I guess further discussion is required on the last two points."}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2013-04-04 21:01:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Abandoned

OK, lets not expend any more energy on this. I'm going to start looking into aws-cfn-bootstrap."}]

commit_message:
Store build-time settings

This will write two files in /etc/ that contain the environment and
command line arguments used in the creation of an image. This should
assist with later efforts to repeat the creation of an image.

Change-Id: Icdbe6693380bed6c406feee10d2cb1a88a992932

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-03-01 09:43:53.000000000', 'message': "Add CRUD methods for tags to the EC2 API.

This is an incomplete implementation of the EC2 tags API.  In EC2, most
resources are able to be tagged.  See
http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/Using_Tags.html

In openstack, the only currently 'taggable' resource is an instance, as
it has an instance_metadata table associated.  So far, only instance
tagging has been implemented, but it is relatively simple to extend this
to other resource types by creating the associated model and api calls.

Additionally, in EC2 searches, shell-style globs are allowed, eg:
fo* will match fo, foo, foobar
fo? will match foo

This has been left to do at a later date.

DocImpact: Adds new API calls: CreateTags, DeleteTags, DescribeTags
See:
http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/APIReference/ApiReference-query-CreateTags.html
http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/APIReference/ApiReference-query-DeleteTags.html
http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/APIReference/ApiReference-query-DescribeTags.html

Fixes: bug #1096821
Implements: blueprint ec2-tags-api

Change-Id: Idf1108f6a3476cabdbdb32ff41c00aa4bc2d9ffe
Signed-off-by: Stephen Gran <stephen.gran@guardian.co.uk>

commit_message:
Add CRUD methods for tags to the EC2 API.

This is an incomplete implementation of the EC2 tags API.  In EC2, most
resources are able to be tagged.  See
http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/Using_Tags.html

In openstack, the only currently 'taggable' resource is an instance, as
it has an instance_metadata table associated.  So far, only instance
tagging has been implemented, but it is relatively simple to extend this
to other resource types by creating the associated model and api calls.

Additionally, in EC2 searches, shell-style globs are allowed, eg:
fo* will match fo, foo, foobar
fo? will match foo

This has been left to do at a later date.

DocImpact: Adds new API calls: CreateTags, DeleteTags, DescribeTags
See:
http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/APIReference/ApiReference-query-CreateTags.html
http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/APIReference/ApiReference-query-DeleteTags.html
http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/APIReference/ApiReference-query-DescribeTags.html

Fixes: bug #1096821
Implements: blueprint ec2-tags-api

Change-Id: Idf1108f6a3476cabdbdb32ff41c00aa4bc2d9ffe
Signed-off-by: Stephen Gran <stephen.gran@guardian.co.uk>

commit_message:
Fix mysql migration script to handle errors.

Errors in mysqldump would have been missed due to not having pipefail
set. Also there was a type-o in the invocation of mysqldump that was
going undetected, that has been repaired. Finally we should not pass
--master-data if we don't have slave credentials, as the master data,
even if provided, is useless without a valid slave user/pass.

Change-Id: I0f80af34c747f465250ef17fae4a44dac919c9cd

commit_message:
Remove strict sql_mode setting which breaks apps.

Strict sql_mode settings are very application specific, many will simply
not work with them. This setting was likely inherited from some other
production MySQL config file and is not appropriate for a generic
configuration. Specifically, this broke the MySQL package maintainer
scripts.

Change-Id: I068fcc7b3c770541d3d1ecfb372384750f182584

is actually in the main nova code base now.

commit_message:
Move console scripts to entrypoints.

As part of the move of plugins to entrypoints, take advantage of the
entrypoints based console scripts, which will make our command line scripts
available for unittesting.

Part of blueprint entrypoints-plugins

Co-authored-by: Michael Still <mikal@stillhq.com>

Change-Id: I5f17348b7b3cc896c92263dd518abb128757d81f

commit_message:
Do not require arguments for os-svc-daemon.

They are not actually required, so allow os-svc-daemon to be called
without them.

Change-Id: I62c2887d48e4173005c54c9cab4ecd6aff8069a1

commit_message:
Add expected IDs to router.interface.* notifications

Fixes bug 1160431

The router.interface.{create|delete} notifications are intended to be
consumed by ceilometer, but did not include the router or tenant IDs
in the RPC message payload. Ceilometer requires both these data for
metering purposes.

The missing UUIDs are now provided in the notifications.

Change-Id: I1ca6e1d5377100a0549293e0bdff0182711c750f

Use operating system supplied python extensions.

Rather than compile lxml, sqlalchemy, etc. at 'pip install' time, use the OS
supplied versions.

commit_message:
Use format_message on exceptions instead of str()

This patch changes all usages of unicode() and str() in the API layer
(and most other reasonable places) into a new format_message method.
This is done in order to avoid leaking the stack trace back to the
user through the Remote excepitons.

This patch deliberately avoids the EC2 api as the way how the EC2 API
handles responses is being worked on as part of another blueprint.

Fixes bug 1159755

(cherry picked from commit 86031940b313532606449c400bca64707be1797a)

Conflicts:

	nova/api/openstack/compute/contrib/admin_actions.py
	nova/api/openstack/compute/contrib/agents.py
	nova/api/openstack/compute/contrib/console_output.py
	nova/api/openstack/compute/contrib/consoles.py

[{'created': '2013-03-28 18:31:03.000000000', 'message': 'Add a format_message method to the Exceptions

This patch adds a format_message method to the NovaException class that
will almost always do what a user wants, when they want to print out the
message of the exception.

Exceptions that are received through RPC are turned into an actual
exception classes by the deserialize_remote_exception function of the
nova.openstack.common.rpc.common module. This function then overrides
__str__ and __unicode__ methods of a new class to print the whole trace.
We still want to preserve this functionality (for logging) but do not
want to leak the trace back to the user in the HTTP response.

Based on the above, This patch attempts to establish a convention that
states: if you need to get the message of a NovaException subclass -
always use the format_message method. Only use str(e) or unicode(e) when
you suspect that they were overriden.

Initially this was attempted through adding a custom metaclass to the
NovaException class so that format_message cannot be overridden in
subclasses, however due to a bug in testtools - many tests were failing.
A patch was proposed to testtols to remedy this
(https://github.com/testing-cabal/testtools/pull/34) however until it is
merged, we cannot use metaclasses with our exception classes as they
cause tests to fail.

(cherry picked from commit b936df8c1ec47300540403ebb6833f0fbf5f195f)

Conflicts:

	nova/tests/test_exception.py

Change-Id: I0a399b9ab3227bad644b031c9b689fe0ce64586e
'}]
commit_message:
Add a format_message method to the Exceptions

This patch adds a format_message method to the NovaException class that
will almost always do what a user wants, when they want to print out the
message of the exception.

Exceptions that are received through RPC are turned into an actual
exception classes by the deserialize_remote_exception function of the
nova.openstack.common.rpc.common module. This function then overrides
__str__ and __unicode__ methods of a new class to print the whole trace.
We still want to preserve this functionality (for logging) but do not
want to leak the trace back to the user in the HTTP response.

Based on the above, This patch attempts to establish a convention that
states: if you need to get the message of a NovaException subclass -
always use the format_message method. Only use str(e) or unicode(e) when
you suspect that they were overriden.

Initially this was attempted through adding a custom metaclass to the
NovaException class so that format_message cannot be overridden in
subclasses, however due to a bug in testtools - many tests were failing.
A patch was proposed to testtols to remedy this
(https://github.com/testing-cabal/testtools/pull/34) however until it is
merged, we cannot use metaclasses with our exception classes as they
cause tests to fail.

(cherry picked from commit b936df8c1ec47300540403ebb6833f0fbf5f195f)

Conflicts:

	nova/tests/test_exception.py

Change-Id: I0a399b9ab3227bad644b031c9b689fe0ce64586e

commit_message:
Migrate data into MySQL from bootstrap.

Use Heat Metadata to specify host and credentials to pull whole database
snapshot and setup Replication. Also include root credentials for use after
the snapshot has been applied.

Change-Id: Ie3aa92463d28db54a523f520c2b4cdfb528acf9d

Run os-config-applier using os-refresh-config.

There's no need to run os-config-applier at any time except when
os-refresh-config is in its configure state.

commit_message:
Adding checks when updating a quota

The rd-client is changing to no longer accept all resources when updating a quota.
The client will then send 'None' values to resources that are not to be updated.
This fix ensures that the changes in the client are handled.

This effort was initiated by the implementation of quota for backups

Change-Id: I24e02a2736750a2606d62dfd06f0130bef503b10

commit_message:
Disable tunneling in quantum-ovs.

Quantum-ovs was continually re-creating interfaces
every second or so, because it was configured to use tunneling,
and the default version of OVS included with ubuntu does
not support tunneling.

Change-Id: I1246181c4b9c96ebe2795b337454dc8ddcb35e8f

commit_message:
Optimize resource tracker queries for instances

instance_get_all_by_host_and_node() had 4 different joins being done.
The resource tracker is the only consumer of this method and does not
need the joins.  This optimization will save many unnecessary rows from
being fetched during the update_available_resource() audit task.

Change-Id: I414c219e4563634e270007fe3d0fa980b273e795

commit_message:
Allow deletion of backups where the service is None

In the case of a backup being created with the configured backup service
not running (as in the case of devstack, if swift has not been enabled),
backup records are created in the database with a service entry of None.
There is no actual backup data created on the service, since the service
isn't running. This fix allows removal of these records without an error
when a delete backup request is received.

Fixes bug #1162908

Change-Id: I4c92bcd145797af1f8b65d92933405215e715c00

subject: Check if key in system_metadata before deletion.
messages:
[{'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-04-04 15:52:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

So, isn't it a bug if we call the delete function on something that doesn't have the stashed types? I'd really rather fix the call sites than make these functions just silently ignore situations like this, because it means there is likely another place that expects to fetch out a type from sys_meta where silently ignoring the absence isn't an option.

Recently I changed the migrate code to always stash both the old and new, regardless of whether we are changing types or not for simplicity in the later paths.

Where is this being called from that it's failing?"}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2013-04-04 16:13:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Dan, apparently I had not pulled from trunk before tracing the code path.  It looks like you did fix this almost two weeks ago, and the bug I'm fixing is moot.  I considered making a change similar to yours, but I also liked the idea of protecting a del that can put an instance in ERROR just because some data it may not need isn't there.

The offending call was the _cleanup_stored_instance_types from confirm_resize, but it should no longer be an issue."}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2013-04-04 16:13:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2013-04-04 15:49:26.000000000', 'message': 'Check if key in system_metadata before deletion.

During confirm_resize an attempt is made to delete old instance type
data from system_metadata.  This is not guaranteed to exist, such as a
resize occurring with no change in flavor.  Now we ensure a key exists
before attempting to delete it.

Bug 1164577

Change-Id: I9d0066cd3e3358e9738985fd0195fb040014d70a

commit_message:
Check if key in system_metadata before deletion.

During confirm_resize an attempt is made to delete old instance type
data from system_metadata.  This is not guaranteed to exist, such as a
resize occurring with no change in flavor.  Now we ensure a key exists
before attempting to delete it.

Bug 1164577

Change-Id: I9d0066cd3e3358e9738985fd0195fb040014d70a

commit_message:
No longer pass no_cache=True to novaclient create

The default is now os_cache=False, so default behaviour will not
use a keyring that prompts for a password.

This was committed on 2012-12-12 and released in
python-novaclient 2.11.0 on 2013-02-11

Part of blueprint auth-token-only

Change-Id: Id2846b2e344f8e3321240795aebf9a59ddad711a

commit_message:
Allow nova operations with only auth_token

This uses the same technique as Horizon for auth_token operations.

Specifically, the nova endpoint is found directly from keystone
and the auth_token and management_url are set on novaclient
after it has been created.

Note that the explicit call to authenticate() is not required
and actually breaks the auth_token case.

Tested by launching a stack with and without the --token-only flag

Also tested using Horizon, which is auth_token only

Part of blueprint auth-token-only

Change-Id: Ic11a838b96a4b5130cb2ac9d685e8a97c9d0a0ad

This uses the same technique as Horizon for auth_token operations.

Specifically, the cinder endpoint is found directly from keystone
and the auth_token and management_url are set on cinderclient
after it has been created.

Client libs are in theory capable of looking up their own endpoints
given an auth_token, but in practice this is the code-path least
travelled and there are many issues. I think it is best to do what
Horizon does, since all Horizon operations use only a token and always
provide the endpoint to the client lib.

Tested by launching a stack with and without the --token-only flag

Also tested using Horizon, which is auth_token only

Part of blueprint auth-token-only

commit_message:
Allow cinder operations with only auth_token

This uses the same technique as Horizon for auth_token operations.

Specifically, the cinder endpoint is found directly from keystone
and the auth_token and management_url are set on cinderclient
after it has been created.

Client libs are in theory capable of looking up their own endpoints
given an auth_token, but in practice this is the code-path least
travelled and there are many issues. I think it is best to do what
Horizon does, since all Horizon operations use only a token and always
provide the endpoint to the client lib.

Tested by launching a stack with and without the --token-only flag

Also tested using Horizon, which is auth_token only

Part of blueprint auth-token-only

Change-Id: Iea9159299ad3f354bcc768c9ac1172d6d9f814a8

[{'created': '2013-04-01 15:35:43.000000000', 'message': "Support overriding oslo localedir too

Part of fixing bug #995287

Libraries need to translate strings according to their translation
domain but they should not override the default _() builtin (which
should only be installed by the top-level script) and instead should
gettextutils._().

To support the case where message catalogs are installed in a
non-default (and perhaps project-specific) location, we allow the
default localedir to be override with a project-specific environment
variable e.g. QUANTUMCLIENT_LOCALEDIR.

The code makes it seem like OSLO_LOCALEDIR is the env variable we're
adding but, in fact, update.py magically replaces 'oslo' with the
project name.

Change-Id: I62b66892a4e27892ee488d2884ffd2f40ab467ee

commit_message:
Support overriding oslo localedir too

Part of fixing bug #995287

Libraries need to translate strings according to their translation
domain but they should not override the default _() builtin (which
should only be installed by the top-level script) and instead should
gettextutils._().

To support the case where message catalogs are installed in a
non-default (and perhaps project-specific) location, we allow the
default localedir to be override with a project-specific environment
variable e.g. QUANTUMCLIENT_LOCALEDIR.

The code makes it seem like OSLO_LOCALEDIR is the env variable we're
adding but, in fact, update.py magically replaces 'oslo' with the
project name.

Change-Id: I62b66892a4e27892ee488d2884ffd2f40ab467ee

[{'created': '2013-04-01 15:35:42.000000000', 'message': "Add a gettextutils.install() helper function

Part of fixing bug #995287

Every top-level script in every project needs to call gettext.install()
so that a _() builtin function is installed and strings are translated
using the correct translation domain.

However, translations are always installed in the default localedir
(which is commonly '/usr/share/locale') and, in cases like devstack, may
be found in a project-specific localedir. To support such a use case we
should have project-specific environment variables for overriding the
default value of localedir - e.g. NOVA_LOCALEDIR.

Add a new gettextutils.install() helper method to make this as easy as
possible for projects to get right.

Change-Id: I6c8549c8ff00797c96f2dd4b0b5266d18d77aa19

commit_message:
Add a gettextutils.install() helper function

Part of fixing bug #995287

Every top-level script in every project needs to call gettext.install()
so that a _() builtin function is installed and strings are translated
using the correct translation domain.

However, translations are always installed in the default localedir
(which is commonly '/usr/share/locale') and, in cases like devstack, may
be found in a project-specific localedir. To support such a use case we
should have project-specific environment variables for overriding the
default value of localedir - e.g. NOVA_LOCALEDIR.

Add a new gettextutils.install() helper method to make this as easy as
possible for projects to get right.

Change-Id: I6c8549c8ff00797c96f2dd4b0b5266d18d77aa19

commit_message:
Copy recent changes in periodic tasks from nova.

The nova periodic task code has moved on. Bring oslo inline with
the new code. The next step after this is to update Quantum (the
only user of this code I can find) to the new interface, and then
move nova across to using this code.

Change-Id: I3f041ca9a6ba9f0e5be4b29198d16454c9797fef

commit_message:
NetApp[Backport]: Clean up QTree when deleting volume

Previously, deleting a Cinder volume would leave a QTree on NetApp
storage box. This commit fixes the issue.

Fixes bug 1099414

Change-Id: I95f1d6b802f4abfad421d34f1c000b75fb72c41e

commit_message:
Prevents flavors to be deleted when reusing a name

Adds an extra check to the EditFlavor form
in order to avoid losing the flavor if an
existing name is setted as the new name.

This control is needed because the current
edit implementation is based in a
delete-create action.

Change-Id: I4251c64fa4719831a1ed949bf95349a350dd303d

commit_message:
Remove internal store references from migration 017

Migration 017 was accessing a object internal to the swift store driver
and changing its behavior in order to do the migration. This worked but
it made the assumption that the driver logic would not change without
also changing the migration code.  This patch removes all dependencies on
the swift driver from the migration code.  This patch is smilar to
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/24552/.

Fixes bug: 1155749
Change-Id: Iffd800f62d61bf7608f7be5b23d76d702e6d4064

commit_message:
Reordering of optional and required args in lbaas commands help

In help info required args are changed to go after optional. The change
affects 'lb-healthmonitor-create' and 'lb-member-create' commands.

Fixes bug 1157502

Change-Id: I5bb2337796c8b725333ed23a662061a4f276985c

commit_message:
Add public api to get authentication info from client

auth info (in particular token and endpoint_url) can be reused
in different quantum client instances to reduce roundtrips with keystone

fixes bug 1150051

Change-Id: I3b2f23f364099bdb08992130d5edb87222e8d387

commit_message:
Convert storage drivers to return models

Update the storage drivers to return instances of models classes
instead of dictionaries to ensure that they always return the same
values.

The get_volume_sum(), get_volume_max(), and get_event_interval()
methods are not modified because there will be another changeset
later replacing the use of those methods with calls to
get_meter_statistics().

blueprint storage-api-models

Change-Id: I79da8cc69f70a4f4c24aa13e6a5d2982011eee88
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug.hellmann@dreamhost.com>

[{'created': '2013-04-02 23:44:15.000000000', 'message': 'Log tracepath for stack validate exceptions.

Calling validate on each resource exercises a lot of code, and
will at times cause non-validation related exceptions.

This change just logs the tracepath for any exception that happens
during validate.

This may be a contender for backporting to milestone-proposed,
since diagnosing some problems on the grizzly branch will be
difficult without it

Change-Id: Ib010a8ec826552e2817da3a22c633dcac6c3ffc6
Fixes: bug #1163586
'}]
commit_message:
Log tracepath for stack validate exceptions.

Calling validate on each resource exercises a lot of code, and
will at times cause non-validation related exceptions.

This change just logs the tracepath for any exception that happens
during validate.

This may be a contender for backporting to milestone-proposed,
since diagnosing some problems on the grizzly branch will be
difficult without it

Change-Id: Ib010a8ec826552e2817da3a22c633dcac6c3ffc6
Fixes: bug #1163586

The existing code assumes that `legacy_net_info` is always in legacy
mode, meaning a list of tuples which causes it to break when passed a
new-style NetworkInfo object.

Fixes bug 1164152

Change-Id: I2131d9b24045cd7531454b65d97776b11ec3ab02
'}]
commit_message:
Fix legacy_net_info guard

The existing code assumes that `legacy_net_info` is always in legacy
mode, meaning a list of tuples which causes it to break when passed a
new-style NetworkInfo object.

Fixes bug 1164152

Change-Id: I2131d9b24045cd7531454b65d97776b11ec3ab02

Created bug 1156269 to cover the case of disks not deleted.'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2013-03-18 19:19:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I dug deeper into this, and it looks like reap is going to crash if this patch lands. If...
- the instance is not deleted during init_host
- the instance also won't start during init_host
- and we assume that the driver will list local instances, even if they aren't running (libvirt, at least, does this)
- then _running_deleted_instances will return the instance because it is defined locally (even though it's not actually running)

The problem is this leads to cleanup_running_deleted_instances calling _shutdown_instance on an instance which is NOT actually running! Particularly if the network for this instance has already been deleted (which is exactly what this patch tries to address), then _shutdown_instance will fail in the same way, and also not call driver.destroy() ..."}, {'account_id': 2835, 'date': '2013-03-18 19:26:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

'}, {'account_id': 1528, 'date': '2013-03-25 15:02:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thanks a lot to Devananda for picking the change up while I was away!

Regarding Brian's earlier comment - "What reaping task are you referring to? If get_instance_nw_info raises InstanceNotFound, what will call the driver destroy method?"

I was under the impression that the better way to handle this is to leave the instance to the periodic task in "_cleanup_running_deleted_instances". It seems oddly specific that new patches are only calling driver.delete, while reaping already handles that within _shutdown_instance(). Reaping also deals with other bits that may be laying around after a failed migration - networking, volumes, usage notifications, etc. That task already runs with read_deleted="yes" switched on temporarily, so it can deal with things that shouldn't exist.

I may be incorrect here, but should we really call only driver.destroy() in this case?'}, {'account_id': 2835, 'date': '2013-03-25 15:43:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Stanislaw's point is good.  There is already cleanup logic in the _cleanup_running_deleted_instances task that shuts down the instance, cleans up volumes, etc.  

Do we need another separate cleanup method, or can this get DRY'd up?"}, {'account_id': 5174, 'date': '2013-03-26 16:34:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2013-03-26 20:30:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2013-03-27 22:54:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Brian, Stanislaw,

unless I'm mistaken, the "other cleanup logic" in _cleanup_running_deleted_instances will *also* fail in exactly the same way. Namely, it will call _shutdown_instance, which calls _get_instance_nw_info again, and that will just raise, because the instance doesn't exist any more!

That is why we need to just directly call driver.destroy here...'}, {'account_id': 2835, 'date': '2013-03-28 14:53:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

commit_message:
After migrate, catch and remove deleted instances

On the host init, starting with a deleted instance which has been
previously evacuated from the host results in an InstanceNotFound
exception. Catch and log this, and then call driver.destroy() so
that the hypervisor driver can clean up the deleted instance.

If we don't do this during host init, it will cause problems during
periodic tasks.

Fixes bug 1155152

Co-authored-by: Devananda van der Veen <devananda.vdv@gmail.com>

Change-Id: I979a698b8e739b9335f37b81e789285f91977a8e

commit_message:
Guard against content being None

`content` can be passed in as None, so we need to set it to the empty
list if that occurs.

This also fixes the bad-practice of using a mutable data-type as a
default argument.

Fixes bug 1163598

Change-Id: Ie991c9452a21cfb036d3955a094ec345805d63d1

commit_message:
Fix resize2fs to accept filesystems on partitioned images

The resize2fs method will blindly try to fsck and resize an image. This is
problematic for images that may have multiple partitions. This patch tries
checking the given image to see if it has a partition table. If it does, and
if the filesystem type is an extended filesystem, it is resized. See
bug #1075356

Change-Id: I0aec15ff987270349f3c09601160cdf513202291

some general notes.

We're trying to move away from kpartx: https://bugs.launchpad.net/bugs/1024586

Also virt-resize might be a more general solution: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/resize-no-raw

There is also the consideration that we might leave resizing of more complicated images to the images themselves, through cloud-init."}, {'account_id': 4912, 'date': '2013-03-23 00:28:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

There are some valid concerns with using kpartx. I feel like we should make a best effort with kpartx as not everyone will be running 3.2 or newer kernel. The most recent version of CentOS 6 for example is still on a 2.6.32 kernel. Could we get some checking code written? It would be really nice to have that for all the other places we are running kpartx. Something like this:

with kpartx_sanity_checks:
    utils.execute('kpartx', .....)

Otherwise this code looks good."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2013-03-23 16:43:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I think this is better handled by the cloud-init resizing code which was recently much improved. That way the image itself can handle resizing itself, and nova doesn't have to worry about it."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2013-03-27 09:20:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I tend to think that we should either delegate this work to virt-resize, or just get out of the filesystem resize business entirely & leave it to the guest OS. The direction this patch is taking is just creating a very poor imitation of what virt-resize can do, and exposes the host kernel to attacks from malicious user disk images which might try to crash the kernel filesystem drivers. http://libguestfs.org/guestfs.3.html#security"}, {'account_id': 1082, 'date': '2013-03-27 14:22:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I definitely fall into the same category as Josh here.
this is not something the hypervisor should do."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-03-27 15:28:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Do not merge

Delete traces of in-progress snapshot on instance being deleted

Catch exception from snapshot process and remove the image being
saved if instance was in fact deleted.

Resolves bug 1143659.

shouldn't this wait until the QA cycles in the RC finish?"}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2013-03-19 15:20:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

There are two ways of seeing it... One is that the release candidate should not change when it's "blessed" to be the final release, in which case you switch versioning to "Final" before the first RC. Or you actually want Final to only show on the final (and don't care that much about the minimal change at release time) and you flip the switch shortly before release. personally I have a slight preference for the former (to minimize stuff we have to do at "release" time), but since Swift is the only project using this "Final" versioning (the others just use the tag to identify the real "Final"), I'll let you pick what you prefer.'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2013-03-19 15:25:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Do not merge

Historically, we've only marked as "final" after QA has been done, so I'd like to keep with that for now.

Marking as -2 to make sure a misclick doesn't merge it too soon. As soon as we have QA signoff, I'll merge this.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2013-03-19 15:32:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2013-03-19 15:32:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Note that install guide also works for 12.04

I had feedback to the effect that people were ignoring this
install guide because it appeared not to work for ubuntu 12.04,
which is untrue.

Explictly labelling this means that those looking to run openstack
on Ubuntu's Long Term Supported release will know this guide can
also be used.

Change-Id: I61940132ac2bc26c91dde95713e48123db45fb15

commit_message:
Added documentation about GlusterFS volume support.

A small mention of Gluster was added to getstart.xml. A full description
of its options was added to the Block Storage guide. Finally, a table
was modified in the Ops guide to show it now has volume support.

Patchset adds more explanation about sparsed volumes settings.
Merge with master.

Change-Id: I36cb344e63f1bddf4125084e02ac507f56591a11
Fixes: bug #1117767

commit_message:
Streamline upstart scripts in os-svc-daemon

Best practice is to use start-stop-daemon rather than sudo, as sudo will
apply user-centric pam limits and create a wtmp entry. Also there is no
need for a script stanza, as we are only execing one command.

Change-Id: I0c2f12536b56d90fd43ab40e74424350efcc0b61

commit_message:
Add a nova-baremetal element.

Future work is intended to allow this to serve
as a nova-virt element as well, by allowing the config
and which services are run (such as bm-deploy-helper)
based upon metadata config settings.

Change-Id: I59718a0b329e6adc59097492638cf02c76162c0a

commit_message:
Replace glance-api+glance-reg elements with glance:

'glance' element now results in a properly-configured,
working glance service on first boot.

While glance-api and glance-reg may need to be broken
out again in the future, the intention now is to focus
on a working service for an end-to-end PoC.

Change-Id: I4fb1cd5ad6defef5a5c4fddfded46d51e8097b5a

commit_message:
Add element to run DHCP on all network interfaces.

Ensures that all network interfaces are present in
/etc/network/interfaces. Any interface not already defined there
will be added and configured for DHCP.

Change-Id: I27e0902e62804e8d719acd7288109bd0e294fd16

commit_message:
Functional tests display the logs of the services they started

Function tests fork out processes that run glance-{api,registry,etc}.
These services are started with a conf file that directs logging
to a different file.  Unfortunately that logged information is not
recorded by the test frameworks that run these tests.  This change
opens the log file and dumps it out to a logger created for that
service.  In this way a developer can inspect the logs of all the
services created by a failed tests using the test frameworks interface
(like Jenkins web interface).

Fixes bug: 1162933

Change-Id: Ie699baaa376ca4ec848a8600f9fc5da6484b24f0

commit_message:
Enhancing the quota feature to remove the hard requirements for quota update

Quota update no longer requires to have all the resources to be passed.
Just the resources to be updated are sufficient.

This effort is needed for quota backup

Change-Id: Ied8bf699db83f2322052ac29f2271a80d64f64d5

commit_message:
Simplify and correct the bm partition sizes.

The sfdisk code that landed uses -D, which ends up subtracting space
from the first partition - this plays havoc with precisely sized disk
images due to a bug in the automatic adjustment code. Instead we
directly specify the spare space to be allowed.

Additionally, sfdisk can be used much more simply, avoiding any room
for us to make arithmetic errors, and reducing the opportunity for
race conditions with udev so this change does that.

Change-Id: I7f95e867d8775f49698cbbf4b1be40e69db9d538

commit_message:
Fix container-server sorting for manifest listings.

The current code will always contact the container server for the
first replica of the container; this fixes it to use the same
backend-sort as all the other places in the proxy that talk to
backends.

Change-Id: If1c168b95bfc5cd120036869f3066549b7a1000a

commit_message:
Prevent creating a single IP address sized network (network details)

The backport for bug #1102504 was incomplete and did not cover
providing the same error message when creating a subnet from the
network details page.

This additional patch is not needed on the master branch, as subnet
creation was refactored during the grizzly cycle.

Fixes bug #1149890

Change-Id: I451e37c347a6540825ad9bf66d4a32c39601dd19

commit_message:
Added Check for Cinder Volume during Start-Deps

    modified "start-deps" so that it checks to see if volume-group
    needs to reconnected (often after a reboot of instance)
    updated docs to show steps for reboot recovery

Change-Id: Idde4ca6e04645c905b2e02486a08f276977a72df

commit_message:
Grizzly release prep - old releases, bugs deleted

This patch is the result of searching the documentation for
references to old releases, fixed bugs et al. It attempts to
remove and update information that will be obsolete when these
docs are released for Grizzly.

patch2 removes references to deprecated versions of ubuntu (11.10
 being the most recent)

Rebased after merging in changes for Grizzly to the install guide.

patch4 addresses Anne's comments

Rebased again, ready to merge.

Change-Id: Id57808802eed66145aa683240000f4f3e90706d0

[{'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-03-22 13:53:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Can you explain more about what the problem is and how this patch solves this?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-03-22 14:14:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- http://logs.openstack.org/25131/1/check/gate-swift-pep8/1953 : SUCCESS
- http://logs.openstack.org/25131/1/check/gate-swift-docs/1784 : SUCCESS
- http://logs.openstack.org/25131/1/check/gate-swift-python26/2032 : SUCCESS
- http://logs.openstack.org/25131/1/check/gate-swift-python26-rhel6/9 : SUCCESS (non-voting)
- http://logs.openstack.org/25131/1/check/gate-swift-python27/2034 : SUCCESS
- http://logs.openstack.org/25131/1/check/gate-tempest-devstack-vm-full/10046 : SUCCESS
- http://logs.openstack.org/25131/1/check/gate-tempest-devstack-vm-quantum/15521 : SUCCESS
- http://logs.openstack.org/25131/1/check/gate-tempest-devstack-vm-postgres-full/9761 : SUCCESS
'}, {'account_id': 6529, 'date': '2013-03-22 14:22:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Metadata in swift stores in list of different xattrs with names user.swift.metadata, user.swift.metadata2 and so on.
Value of each of this attributes can not be more then 254 bytes. So swift pickle metadata and then split into parts 254 bytes each.

In unit test we read only first xattr so if we increase metadata by adding some new information, test will fail.

I use object server function for reading metadata, so test will correctly work longer variants of metadata.'}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2013-03-22 15:31:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Isn't the size of the metadata configurable?"}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2013-03-22 18:10:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Sam wrote in the bug "If you submit the test change on its own, I predict that it will either be ignored in Gerrit or you'll get other people asking why you're making changes to an already-passing test." And they did!

In this case there's no downside, so +1. However in general we need the use case.'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-03-22 23:41:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

So can one demonstrate how additional information in a test will show the failure so that we see the concrete case?'}, {'account_id': 6529, 'date': '2013-03-26 10:12:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

https://github.com/Mirantis/swift-encrypt.git
Here you can watch changes what we do to the swift. It's a big chnges but main for this bug is only the fact that we add some more metadata information and unittest starts to fails.
I research this question and found that problem is in way of reading xattr. Maybe some other developer will increase metadata and it would be better if they will not make this research again.
Because of the fact that bug was transferred into triaged state I decide to commit it."}, {'account_id': 2828, 'date': '2013-03-27 06:48:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

'}, {'account_id': 995, 'date': '2013-04-03 20:14:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-04-03 20:14:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

Starting gate jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-04-03 20:55:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified

commit_message:
Add du to rootwrap filters

Setting "nfs_disk_util=du" or "glusterfs_disk_util=du" will use
du instead of df for space calculation, but du is not allowed by
rootwrap.

Change-Id: I35522d40f97ea14cacf2637603f06a15810a0b36

commit_message:
Change format of some judgments

Because "not volume" will be True if volume id is 0.It can not
distinguish 0 from None.The same to some other judgments where
variable value may be 0.

This patch also does the following changes:
Deletes check storagepool in function _check_conf_file and adds
check default iscsi target IP in function initialize_connection.
Moves create host group from do_setup to initialize_connection.
Changes _get_login_info to be _update_login_info.

Fixes bug: 1160340
Change-Id: I0434b587d57c783f10d5724c4c66aea5df0b32e5

commit_message:
Return (claim_id, message_iter) in SQLite create().

In general, POST should respond only the things not in users'
requests.  Similar to post() messages, which returns the msgids,
we return the created claim id, plus the claimed messages.

commit_message:
Replaces ugettext with ugettext_lazy in the dashboard-related files

While most files correctly import ugettext_lazy, some are importing ugettext instead.
This is causing some parts of the dashboard to not translate correctly when a user
switches languages. The core cause of this is because ugettext will translate the
string once when the django application starts. ugettext_lazy will translate when the
string is retrieved.

Change-Id: I44a394f4cda3b0f019e5a4601d4fa44fc110f939
Fixes: bug #1124276

In the test_scrubber.py the function wait_for_scrub() makes a
reference to self even tho it is not a member of any class and
has no such reference in its scope.  This patch makes that
function a method in the test class so that it can assert the
failure which it intends.

fixes bug: 1163617

Change-Id: I453c8097363dc2f7577fd807ffe8cbc613078258
'}]
commit_message:
Invalid reference to self in functional test test_scrubber.py

In the test_scrubber.py the function wait_for_scrub() makes a
reference to self even tho it is not a member of any class and
has no such reference in its scope.  This patch makes that
function a method in the test class so that it can assert the
failure which it intends.

fixes bug: 1163617

Change-Id: I453c8097363dc2f7577fd807ffe8cbc613078258

commit_message:
Pin prettytable versions

pip-requires doesn't have any restrictions on prettytable.
We should match up with the pinned version in other projects.

In addition to avoid this problem in the future updated simplejson
to match openstack/requirements as well.

Change-Id: Iabf7ee8b0fd253447d1a65bc1b12906d26176286

   class to drop dependency on a specific network device
 - add route wrapper to IPWrapper class
 - use IPWrapper instead of direct calls to ip route in l3 agent
 - update tests

commit_message:
Use wrappers instead of direct calls to ip route.

 - extract the logic of ip route wrapper into a separate
   class to drop dependency on a specific network device
 - add route wrapper to IPWrapper class
 - use IPWrapper instead of direct calls to ip route in l3 agent
 - update tests

Fixes bug 1133133.

Change-Id: Ic7174b0676d1a565909bb5f6f950376cf8fae8d2

commit_message:
Raise self-formatted exceptions in SQlite.

 - A helper, marconi.tests.util.Expected, is added to replace
   testtools.ExpectedException, since the later one does not obey
   the exception hierarchy.

 - ClaimDoesNotExist is added, similar to MessageDoesNotExist.

Change-Id: I8f592184cbf7f3bdab95e9adef1306055097cb6f

commit_message:
Sync Storwize/SVC driver with Grizzly version.

This patch syncs the Storwize/SVC driver in Folsom with the version now
in Grizzly.  This addresses backport fixes for a number of issues
including:
    FlashCopy state machine errors
    Using prefixes to look up hosts
    Create volume from snapshot now fails if sizes are different rather
        than creating with original size
    Check compression support on driver initialization rather than
        failing on volume create
    Fix Storwize/SVC LUN allocation with holes

This also allows us to keep the Folsom and Grizzly versions almost
exactly the same so as to make maintenance and behavior efficient and
consistent.

Fixes: bug 1157012
Fixes: bug 1142196
Fixes: bug 1149072

Change-Id: I28e9b18c270bdc9573c6b11689bc3d669f4748af

commit_message:
If a user only has 1 keypair, this keypair should be selected by default

When Launching a new instance, it's easy to forget to select a keypair
as it's hidden in another tab. This mitigates the issue by selecting a
keypair automatically when there is only one.

Fixes bug #1125124

Change-Id: I04cd6850b4b5f0901d2f9035af8df53cfb67f8c5

[{'created': '2013-03-08 13:34:35.000000000', 'message': 'Dynamically size the noVNC iframe, fix typos in copy

The iframe for the noVNC console is too small for some users who
like to use GUI on the console.  Leaving the sizes off completely
and letting the browser figure it out causes hilarity to ensue, so
explicitly set the height and width to quasi-sensible values.

Also, the "unavailable" error says "unavailabe"  Fixed.

Fixes Bug 1050316

Addendum:

add an identifier to the iframe rather than using the auto-generated selector

Cherry-picked and squashed from grizzly commits: 68db72b95f and a37779c47d

Change-Id: I17cfa97cdc69f4b58e18d02451da2197c663e0d3
'}]
commit_message:
Dynamically size the noVNC iframe, fix typos in copy

The iframe for the noVNC console is too small for some users who
like to use GUI on the console.  Leaving the sizes off completely
and letting the browser figure it out causes hilarity to ensue, so
explicitly set the height and width to quasi-sensible values.

Also, the "unavailable" error says "unavailabe"  Fixed.

Fixes Bug 1050316

Addendum:

add an identifier to the iframe rather than using the auto-generated selector

Cherry-picked and squashed from grizzly commits: 68db72b95f and a37779c47d

Change-Id: I17cfa97cdc69f4b58e18d02451da2197c663e0d3

commit_message:
Use the right subprocess based on os monkeypatch

This works around the following eventlet bug:

https://bitbucket.org/which_linden/eventlet/issue/92

by using the green version of Popen if os has been
monkeypatched. It also has the side effect of making the ssl
calls not block the reactor for workers that use eventlet.

Master Change ID was: I1457237f52310f0536fbcdcaa42174b17e8edbf5

Change-Id: I5b86f9920754a6ade770a336d21072ab0f36f457
